              "path": "05-marketing/outreach-templates/template-B-press.md",
              "content": "# Outreach Template B — Press / Journalist\n\n**Use for:** Newspapers, magazines, tech/gear publications  \n**Tone:** Efficient, factual, lead with the story\n\n---\n\n**Subject:** New product story: the Dutch oven with an automotive-spec drain port\n\nHi [Name],\n\nI'm the founder of Tallow Native, a new Texas cookware brand. I wanted to briefly pitch a story I think has legs.\n\n**The product:** A cast iron Dutch oven with a precision-threaded drain port in the bottom — modeled on the automotive oil drain plug system (M18×1.5 thread, copper crush washer seal). The user drains hot tallow through the pot bottom into a stainless steel catcher below, using a 12-inch T-handle wrench. No pouring hot fat. No burns.\n\n**The story:** The revival of beef tallow frying among home cooks has been significant — search trends, influencer content, and specialty grocery sales all confirm it. But the cookware market has never addressed the specific challenges of animal fat frying. The Tallow Native system is the first product designed around the complete fat lifecycle: cooking, draining, filtering, storing, and reusing.\n\n**What's interesting:** The innovation isn't kitchen technology — it's applied automotive engineering to a cooking problem. The M18×1.5 spec was chosen specifically because it's proven in demanding applications. The copper crush washer is a mechanic's seal, not a chef's trick.\n\nThis is a first-run, 500-unit product launching [DATE], built by a founder who actually fries in tallow. I can offer:\n- Product samples for review\n- Founder interview\n- Technical specification sheets\n- High-resolution product photography\n\nWould this be of interest for [Publication]? Happy to send a press kit.\n\n— [Founder Name]  \nTallow Native  \npress@tallownative.com | tallownative.com\n\n---\n\n**Alt subject lines:**\n- \"The Dutch oven that drains like an oil pan\"\n- \"New cookware startup solves tallow frying's biggest problem with automotive engineering\"\n- \"Texas brand puts an oil drain plug in a cast iron pot\"\n"
